Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

The dataset TMDB movie data. It contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), from 1960 to 2015 including user ratings and revenue. It contains 21 columns as listed below: columns:

  1. id : id of the movie
  2. imdb_id : id of the movie in the imdb
  3. popularity : popularity of the movie
  4. budget : budget of the movie in US dollars
  5. revenue : revenues made by the movie in US dollars
  6. original_title : original tile of the movie
  7. cast: top cast of the movie
  8. homepage: official website of the movie
  9. director: director of the movie
  10. tagline: tagline of the movie
  11. keywords: keywords of the movie
  12. overview: overview of the movie
  13. runtime: runtime of the movie
  14. genres: genres to which belongs the movies
  15. production_companies: production companies of the movie
  16. release_date: release date of the movie
  17. vote_count
  18. vote_average
  19. release_year: release year of the movie
  20. budget_adj: budget of the movie in terms of 2010 dollars
  21. revenue_adj: revenue of the movie in terms of 2010 dollars

Question(s) for Analysis:¶

Which genres are most filmed of all times?¶

What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high profits?¶

Deleting colmuns¶

Columns such as id,imdb_id, homepage,tagline, keywords, overview,vote_average are not relevant to our questions so they are to be deleted.\ \ Also, we have two sets of columns that might seem similar at first sight: (revenue,budget) and (revenue_adj,budget_adj). For the sake of fair comparaison of revenues and budgets between movies from different years and under different economy situations, we will only keep (revenue_adj,budget_adj). These features provide information in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time.

In [77]:
del_col=['id','imdb_id', 'homepage','tagline', 'keywords', 'overview','vote_average','revenue','budget']
df.drop(del_col, axis=1, inplace=True)

Which genres are all times most filmed?¶

Let's start by reviewing the number of movies filmed for each genre.\ We first need to extract the different genres from the genres column.\ We are going to use the function str.get_dummies() that will help us have a column for each genre. each of these columns will indicate if it is a genre of a given movie (value 1) or not (value 0).

In [88]:
# creating dummy columns from the genres column
dummies_columns = df['genres'].str.get_dummies(sep="|")
df_dummy = pd.concat([df, dummies_columns], axis=1)

Most Filmed Genres in the 20th Century¶

We will create the function plot_one_var to create us plots of different data each time.

In [92]:
def plot_one_var(df,k,label_x,label_y,title):
    '''
    creates  plot of the given variable
    parameters:
    df (pd.Dataframe): data or variable to plot
    k (string): kind of plot ('bar','barh','pie')
    label_x (string): label of the x-axis
    label_y (string): label of the y-axis
    title (string): title of the plot
    '''
    df.plot(kind=k)
    plt.xlabel(label_x)
    plt.ylabel(label_y)
    plt.title(title);
In [93]:
# plotting the most filmed genres in the 20th century

What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high profits?¶

top 30 movies with higher profits¶

the feature revenue_adj alone can't determine the financial gains of a movie as they depend also on budget_adj. For that, we will create a new feature named profit_adj such that: profit_adj= revenue_adj - budget_adj to better reflect the gains of a given movie.\ Through the rest of the analysis, we will refer to the movie that belongs to the top 30 movies with higher profits as top movie.

In [99]:
# creating the profit_adj column
df['profit_adj']=df['revenue_adj']-df['budget_adj']
In [100]:
# creating a dataframe that contains top 30 movies in terms of profits
df_top_profit=pd.merge(pd.DataFrame(df['profit_adj'].sort_values(ascending=False))[:30],df,on='profit_adj',how='inner')

Discussion:¶

In the EDA section, we tried to use visuals and statistics to understand our data and answer the research question. Our analysis provided the following informations:

  • In the 20th century, the most filmed genres are Drama and Comedy
  • The most popular genres of all times are Drama,Action and Thriller
  • The genres with the highest revenues are Action,Adventure,Drama and Crime.
  • The top 3 movies in terms of profits are
    • Star Wars : profit_adj = 2.75 million dollars
    • Avatar : profit_adj = 2.58 million dollars
    • Titanic : profit_adj = 2.23 million dollars
  • The histogram representing the distribution of the popularity of the top 30 movies is skewed to the right. Despite making huge profits, a lot of the top movies don't have high popularity.
  • It looks from the plot of the profits against runtime that the less runtime it has, the highest profit the top movies make.
  • The top 30 movies are filmed by a variety of directors. Most of the directors tend to film at most one film that turns out to be a top movie. This excludes famous directors such as Steven Spielberg (4 top movies) and Peter Jackson (3 top movies).
  • release year and vote count have positive correlation. it means the top movies tend to have more vote count year after year
  • budget and profit_adj have positive correalation: top movies tend to make bigger profits when increasing the budget(bigger investements)
  • popularity and budget_adj have positive correlation: the bigger the investments the more popular the top movies tend to be.

Conclusions¶

After analysing our dataset: The TMDB Dataset, we obtained the following results:

  1. the most filmed genres from 1966 to 2015 are Drama,Crime,Thriller and Action.
  2. The most filmed genres in the 20th century are Drama and Comedy.
  3. The most popular genres from 1960 to 2015 are Drama,Action and Thriller.
  4. The genres with the highest revenues are Action,Adventure,Drama and Crime.
  5. The top 3 movies in terms of profits are Star Wars, Avatar and Titanic.
  6. The top movies tend to have average profits of 1.4 million dollars, average budgets of 1 thousands dollars and average revenues of 1.5 million dollars.
  7. Profits don't imply Popularity: Much of the top movies score poorly on popularity despite making huge profits
  8. The top movies seem to make bigger profits the shorter the runtime is.
  9. Most of the directors seem to film at most one film that turns out to be a top movie. Exceptions include 3 or 4 movies at maximum (in the case of Peter Jackson and Steven Spielsberg).
  10. Recent top movies tend to make bigger profits than the old ones
  11. The top movies tend to make bigger profits the bigger the investments are.
  12. The top movies look to become more popular the bigger the investments are.

Limitations:¶

Our approach in determining the results for the first research question is separating different genres for a given movie. This implies that every genre is equally providing for the popularity and the revenues of the movie, which is not always the case. Sometimes one genre can overshadow the rest and have a bigger weighted participation in the popularity and revenues of the associated movie. It is important to understand this limitation.\ Please note that many factors play a role in causing the popularity or the profits of a given movie such as the cast, the production company, the keywords etc... We could not cover them all in this analysis, but their influence should be taken into account.
